1. Setup and Data Loading
1.1 Imports
Import the required libraries:
  -TensorFlow or PyTorch
  -scikit-learn (splits & metrics)
  -numpy, pandas
  -matplotlib (visualizations)
  -Your model class from src/ml_models.py

1.2 Load Cleaned Metadata
Load : data/skin_tone_labels.csv
This file contains:
  -image_path
  -ITA (target label)
  -fitzpatrick_type
  -subject_id
  -lighting_condition
  -status

Also verify:
  -number of valid rows
  -number of subjects
  -missing values


2. Image Data Pipeline
Goal:
Build a fast, batched image pipeline that:
  -loads images
  -resizes → 224×224
  -normalizes pixel values → 0–1
  -applies light augmentation

  2.1) Required Functions
      Implement the following:
            load_image(path)
            preprocess_image(img)
            augment_image(img)
  2.2) Dataset Pipeline
        using TensorFlow:
          -build a tf.data.Dataset
          -apply .map() for preprocessing
          -shuffle → batch → prefetch

  Expected Output
        Batches with shape: (batch_size, 224, 224, 3)

3. Data Splitting
Goal:
  -Split the dataset into:
    --70% — Training
    --15% — Validation
    --15% — Test

  Method
    -Use: from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

  Make sure:
    -data is shuffled
    -images and ITA values remain aligned

4.  Model Training (ML Algorithm 1 — ITA Regression)
  
  4.1) Initialize the Model
      -Instantiate skin tone classifier from: src/ml_models.py
  4.2) Train the Model
      -Train using:
          --Loss: Mean Squared Error
          --Optimizer: Adam
          --Task: Regression

  4.3) Visualize Loss Curves
        -Plot:
            --Training Loss (MSE)
            --Validation Loss (MSE)

      -These help detect:
          --overfitting
          --underfitting
          --stability of learning
      
5.  Model Evaluation

    5.1) Evaluate on Test Set
          Use: loss, mae = classifier.model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)

    5.2) Key Metric
          -MAE (Mean Absolute Error) in ITA degrees
              --How far predictions are (on average) from the true ITA
              --Lower MAE = better accuracy

6.  Save the Trained Model

Save model weights: classifier.model.save_weights('data/ita_classifier_weights_v1.h5')
  This allows:
    -Fast loading in src/app.py
    -Avoid retraining
    -Consistent reproducibility
